Network interfaces.

A network interface is the kernel's abstraction for a single network connection. It might be a physical ethernet port, a wireless card, a u-s-b adapter, or a virtual interface for a v-p-n or a container. Each one has a name and usually at least one eye-pee address.

You will meet a handful of naming patterns. The loopback interface, called l-o, is the virtual interface for a machine talking to itself, and it is always present. Older ethernet interfaces were named e-t-h-zero, e-t-h-one, and so on, still common inside virtual machines and containers. Modern systems use predictable names based on the hardware's bus and slot, which look like e-n-p-zero-s-three. Wireless interfaces start with w-l, and you will also see bridges created by docker or virtualisation, and tunnel interfaces created by v-p-n software.

The key tool for all of this is the i-p command, and it is worth a clear word about it. In older tutorials you will see commands like if-config, route, and net-stat, but these are deprecated. They have been replaced by i-p, for interfaces and routes, and s-s, for sockets, and you should use those in any new work. The i-p command operates on objects, such as a-d-d-r for addresses, link for the interfaces themselves, and route for the routing table, and within each object you take actions like show, add, del, and set. So you might show all addresses, bring an interface up or down, or add an address to a device. One important caveat: changes made directly with the i-p command are temporary and vanish at the next reboot. For configuration that persists, you use a network manager or your distribution's configuration files, which we turn to next.
